oakcurric:unit-2863
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Everyday life: subject and object pronouns, present tense"@en ;
  curric:slug "everyday-life-subject-and-object-pronouns-present-tense" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils revisit subject and object pronouns, practising them with
  present and perfect tenses. Subject pronouns are used to mean 'it' and 'they, and object
  pronouns to mean 'me' 'you' and 'him, her and it' placed before the verb."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils embed their knowledge of present and past tenses
  whilst revisiting subject and object pronouns.The contraction of pronouns (for example me to
  m') before a vowel or h muet is practised. Pupils apply this knowledge in varying contexts
  including reading habits and life at school. Direct objects and numbers 70-99 are practised
  in the context of shopping.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2863-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2863-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2863-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2863-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2863-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2863-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2863-7 ;
  curric:id "2863"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.076959Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-nouns-and-determiners ,
    oakcurric:thread-extend-written-and-spoken-production .

oakcurric:unit-2832
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "School life: inversion questions and singular common  -RE & -IR verbs"@en ;
  curric:slug "school-life-inversion-questions-and-singular-common-re-and-ir-verbs" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils use singular forms of common irregular -re and -ir verbs
  whilst forming inversion questions with 'tu' and il,elle'. They also practise inversion
  questions with two-verb structures and with five different question words. SSCs ain,in and
  ai are revisited."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit pupils continue to expand their verb lexicon with singular
  forms of common irregular -re verbs (for example prendre and dire) and -ir verbs (for example
  sortir and venir). Pupils extend their range of question forms, adding word order changes
  with inversion questions, including with two-verb structures and question words comment, où,
  quand, quoi and pourquoi. Pupils develop their communicative competence with questions and
  answers in personalising their answers, asking about likes and dislikes and conducting an
  interview.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2832-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2832-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2832-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2832-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2832-5 ;
  curric:id "2832"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.314799Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions .

oakcurric:unit-2831
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Places and people: plural 'aller' and -ER present tense verbs"@en ;
  curric:slug "places-and-people-plural-aller-and-er-present-tense-verbs" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils add the plural forms of 'aller' to their verb lexicon. They
  apply this when using à, 'en' and 'chez' for to' in different contexts. Pupils reactivate
  '-er verbs and mostly known vocabulary in extended reading and writing tasks about famous
  French people. [en,an] is revisited."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils complete their knowledge of 'aller' in the present
  tense in all forms. They also revisit the verb patterns for -er verbs. Revisiting these verb
  patterns with new verbs is essential to securing the knowledge. In addition, they apply it
  with new grammar - the use of à, en and chez meaning 'to' in different contexts. Pupils apply
  their knowledge in a rich cultural context as they learn of the wealth of artistic, fashion
  sporting, scientific and multicultural heritage of famous French speakers.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2831-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2831-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2831-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2831-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2831-5 ;
  curric:id "2831"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.524137Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present .

oakcurric:unit-2836
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Summer activities: modal verbs in two-verb structures"@en ;
  curric:slug "summer-activities-modal-verbs-in-two-verb-structures" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils extend their knowledge of two-verb structures as modal verbs
  with dependent infinitives are introduced. 'Devoir' 'vouloir' and 'pouvoir' in singular
  persons are taught so pupils can express what they want to, have to and can do on
  holidays. SSCs -ien and -tion are revisited."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils enrich their verb lexicon with the highly frequent modal verbs
  'devoir', 'vouloir' and 'pouvoir' in singular persons. These modal verbs with dependent
  infinitives enrich pupils' prior knowledge of two-verb structures, allowing them to use known
  high frequency vocabulary to develop more nuanced communication. Pupils' knowledge of
  questions and negative sentences with modals verbs and dependent infinitives consolidates
  existing grammar knowledge as pupils exploit this in role play contexts, making plans to meet
  up.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2836-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2836-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2836-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2836-4 ;
  curric:id "2836"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.526255Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-the-present ,
    oakcurric:thread-negation .

oakcurric:unit-2861
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Past and present events: perfect tense, negation, questions"@en ;
  curric:slug "past-and-present-events-perfect-tense-negation-questions" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils deepen their knowledge of the perfect tense, question forms and negation.
  '-er verbs taking être in the perfect and the negative 'ne...jamais' are introduced .
  Pupils apply changes in register (tu vs vous, on vs nous), use emphatic pronouns 'moi' and
  'toi' and the relative pronoun 'qui'."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils deepen their knowledge of the perfect tense in a
  range of contexts including historical events, celebrations in other countries, public
  services and a Eurovision song text. Pupils apply their knowledge in extended reading and
  listening, using reference resources, creative writing and in transactional dialogues. Pupils
  anchor the present tense in talking about their free time activities, using the relative
  pronoun 'qui'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2861-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2861-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2861-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2861-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2861-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2861-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2861-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2861-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2861-9 ;
  curric:id "2861"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.550222Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-past ,
    oakcurric:thread-listen-and-respond-to-longer-passages ,
    oakcurric:thread-negation ,
    oakcurric:thread-use-reference-resources ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-read-and-respond-to-texts .

oakcurric:unit-2862
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How things used to be: imperfect tense, ordinal numbers"@en ;
  curric:slug "how-things-used-to-be-imperfect-tense-ordinal-numbers" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils are introduced firstly to -er verbs in the imperfect tense to describe
  habitual events in the past. The imperfect of common irregular verbs is added, before
  pupils then contrast one-off and habitual events with the perfect vs imperfect tenses,
  practising this with known and new vocabulary."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils consolidate their knowledge of the past tense, as
  they add the imperfect tense of -er verbs and frequent irregular verbs (such as prendre,
  venir, sortir lire, choisir, and écrire) to their repertoire. The context of the past and
  present school system in France, and childhood memories of French speaking celebrities
  supports pupils in consolidating the uses of the imperfect tense for habitual activities vs
  the perfect tense for one-off completed events. Pupils will continue to consolidate this in
  extended writing and speaking tasks.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2862-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2862-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2862-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2862-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2862-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2862-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2862-7 ;
  curric:id "2862"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.630171Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-past .

oakcurric:unit-2838
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Jobs: 'avoir' and 'être', feminine nouns"@en ;
  curric:slug "jobs-avoir-and-etre-feminine-nouns" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils revisit 'être', 'avoir', intonation and inversion questions.
  The question structure 'est-ce que' is introduced. Feminine adjective agreement and
  feminine noun formation rules are extended. Liaison with 'h' and stress syllabification
  are introduced, and s-liaison revisited."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit predominantly revisits known vocabulary and grammar in the
  context of people and their jobs. Pupils expand their practise of asking and answering
  questions as 'est-ce que' is introduced. Pupils also expand their accuracy in describing jobs
  using être and profession without an article. Feminine noun and adjective formation rules are
  extended as pupils use these more readily and accurately in reading and responding to texts,
  and in a class survey on future jobs.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2838-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2838-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2838-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2838-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2838-5 ;
  curric:id "2838"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.695625Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-nouns-and-determiners ,
    oakcurric:thread-adjectives ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-be-being ,
    oakcurric:thread-verb-to-have-having ,
    oakcurric:thread-read-and-respond-to-texts .

oakcurric:unit-2851
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Past events: the perfect tense, questions"@en ;
  curric:slug "past-events-the-perfect-tense-questions" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils extend their knowledge of the perfect tense as they practise
  asking intonation, inversion and est-ce que questions in the perfect tense. They learn
  irregular past participles, practise the two English translations (I did, I have done) for
  the French perfect tense"""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils anchor their knowledge of the perfect tense and apply
  it in inversion questions. The English present perfect translation (I have done) is then
  contrasted with the known simple past (I did), and the range of perfect tense questions
  expanded to include intonation and est-ce que questions. Pupils apply this knowledge in
  describing a range of past events. New irregular past participles are introduced as they
  extend their vocabulary, and then consolidate this in a rich text exploitation, where pupils
  explore high frequency vocabulary and grammar in a literary context.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2851-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2851-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2851-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2851-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2851-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2851-6 ;
  curric:id "2851"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.718835Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-cultural-spotlight ,
    oakcurric:thread-the-past ,
    oakcurric:thread-negation ,
    oakcurric:thread-questions ,
    oakcurric:thread-read-and-respond-to-texts .

oakcurric:unit-2844
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Everyday activities: preposition 'de', partitive, frequent -IR and -RE verbs"@en ;
  curric:slug "everyday-activities-preposition-de-partitive-frequent-ir-and-re-verbs" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils embed irregular -ir and -re verbs. They distinguish between jouer à, jouer
  de and faire de, and practise 'de' as a partitive article (du, de la, des, de l'). They
  use de, d in negatives, expressions of quantity and learn adverb positioning. SSCs -s-,
  th, -ill-, -ille, -aill-, -ail are taught."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils reactivate and embed a significant amount of known
  grammar and vocabulary. The key present tense patterns of regular and frequent irregular
  verbs help cement this core knowledge. Plentiful practice of the preposition 'de' with verbs,
  as partitive article and in negatives builds pupils' understanding, accuracy and
  communicative competence as they ask and answer questions about regular activities, daily
  routine and shopping. Both present and past tenses are revisited in extended spoken and
  written production as pupils' competence with different time frames improves.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2844-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2844-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2844-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2844-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2844-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2844-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2844-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2844-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2844-9 ;
  curric:id "2844"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.877036Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-languages-key-stage-3 ;
